optionalComments: The stripped bar charts were confusing. Some paters are very similar which can lead to confusion and mixups. The neutral bar chart was the best in my opinion, as you only need to focus on the product name and verify the quantity in the Y axis acordingly. The imaged bar chart is interesting for color blind people, as you do have a image representation of the product, however I feel this may be limmited to certain products like, for example, if instead of vegetables we where comparing quantities of things that are very similar to each other. I also felt that having too much image in the bars of the bar chart can lead to clustering, this making the iamges too distracting, so Id advice to instead of, lets say 20 carrots, drwan in a big bar just have 1. I also notice I looked more at the names of vegetables to figure out quantities than the paterns, but the images of the vegetables in the bars did help in some cases.

Even though the charts had different textures and drawings inside of each piece, my number one source of getting the answer was by looking at the name of each vegatable and comparing sizes. That's why the first chart (the most simple one) was the better for getting it right
